# interp_string.z -- a binding to an interpolated-String literal with a redundant
# `.string` (`k: "\{a}:\{b}".string`). An interpolated literal is already an owned
# String, so `.string` is identity. The typecheck didn't resolve `.string` on a
# String base (String has no `string` member; only StringView does) -> the binding
# got no type stamp -> "unhandled binding type" -> the local was never declared.
# The reference special-cases `.string` on a String/StringView base to String.
# Mirrors zvfs's `key: "\{parent}:\{name}".string` / `childpath: "...".string`.

main: function is {
    a: "x".string
    b: "y".string
    k: "\{a}:\{b}".string
    print "k=\{k}"
}
